  "name": "The Grammar of Economic Ideas",
  "description": "Fifty-five foundational economic concepts — from Adam Smith to Karl Marx to Elinor Ostrom to Kropotkin — presented without hierarchy between schools of thought. Classical, behavioral, Marxist, anarchist, ecological, and complexity economics sit side by side. Each idea gets a plain-language explanation, a real-world sighting, its common misuse, and threads connecting it to other concepts in the grammar. The goal is not to judge which lens is right, but to make the ideas accessible and see where they weave — or don't.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: William Hogarth's satirical prints on commerce and morality (18th century). Honoré Daumier's lithographs of capitalists and workers (1830s-1870s). Diego Rivera's murals depicting labor and industry. Illustrations from Adam Smith's 'Wealth of Nations' early editions. Soviet constructivist economic posters (1920s-1930s). WPA-era American economic education posters.",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "creator_link": "https://lifeisprocess.substack.com/",
